#Text=The caves are the world’s largest known examples of “flank-margin caves”, a type of cave that develops in carbonate coastlines as a result of sea-water and freshwater mixing inside the coastline.
#Text=Morphometry is the measurement and analysis of form (shape).
#Text=The outstanding landforms are dissolutional corridors (“streets”) in the limestone that follow major vertical fractures created by the doming (Brook & Ford, 1978).
#Text=Paleokarst is a worldwide phenomenon that is found on all continents, including Antarctica, and in the geological record from the early Proterozoic to the Holocene.
#Text=Caves without roofs are an important paleokarst landform which has only recently attracted scientific attention.
#Text=Paleokarst aquifers are important sources of water and can present a significant flooding hazard to underground mining operations.

#Text=Palynology, the study of microscopic organic matter known as palynomorphs (Traverse, 1988), offers enormous potential in karst research since it can provide important evidence about ancient environments.

#Text=Palynology is an integral part of many archaeological investigations in caves, since it provides a picture of the flora close to the cave and thus enables environmental and climatic reconstruction.
#Text=Paragenesis is the term introduced by Renault (1968) to describe the processes by which cave genesis within the phreatic zone is modified by influxes of sediment.
#Text=“Network mazes” are angular grids of intersecting fissures guided by fractures.
#Text=“Spongework mazes” are irregular cavities enlarged from primary pores, which interconnect in a three-dimensional array like the holes in a sponge.

#Text=Large allogenic streams penetrate farther into the karst in well-defined valleys before they sink, and they produce landforms known as blind valleys, because their valleys usually terminate abruptly in a cliff or steep slope.
#Text=A pre-ponor retention is a temporary water accumulation in the surface depression just above the ponor.
#Text=Pseudokarstic caves are natural underground spaces, large enough to enter and investigate, extending beyond daylight, and produced by some process other than dissolution.

#Text=Emanation is the net radon production rate in the rock walls of a cave, or in unconsolidated sediment within the cave, and ultimately depends on the concentration of uranium (which then decays to radium) in the material.
